\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 146.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch However, in marked contrast with Shoprite Checkers, Pick n Pay utilised its own merchandising furniture, including the costly CDUs, apparently because it feared compromising its independence from the supplier.  This having been said, there is no evidence t
hat the provision of free CDUs to Shoprite Checkers ever interfaced with the trade investment agreements.  It appears that in Shoprite Checkers the agreements regarding the CDUs were concluded at store level and there is no evidence that withdrawal or thre
atened withdrawal of the merchandising furniture was ever used to enforce the nationally negotiated trade investment agreements.  We will say more about the provision of CDUs below.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 147.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch As with Shoprite Checkers, Pick n Pay was incentivised to comply with BATSA drivers by the payment of cash incentives.   However it appears that while the agreements regarding the total payment by BATSA to Pick n Pay were concluded at national level, imple
mentation, including the application of regional particularities, was negotiated with the regional buyers.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 148.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch Planogramming in Pick n Pay was attended by even more than the usual uncertainties and disagreements. Hence van Vuuren insists that despite receiving regular compliance payments from BATSA (as well as considerable sums in exchange for Pick n Pay\'92s EPOS dat
a), the Western Cape region of Pick n Pay did not implement planograms submitted by BATSA.  The reason advanced was that he, van Vuuren, had never accepted, never agreed to, any of the planograms proposed by BATSA which he consistently described as mere \'91w
ish lists\'92. However, his refusal to accept or comply with the planograms drawn up by BATSA did not, in van Vuuren\'92s estimation, impact on Pick n Pay\'92s right to receive the full incentive payments from BATSA which, he insisted, he continued to receive.  van
 Vuuren\'92s rather eccentric interpretation of the agreement is that BATSA was obliged to furnish him with a planogram acceptable to him and until that was done Pick n Pay was under no obligation to implement an important element of its side of the bargain \'96
 to implement planograms agreed with BATSA - without thereby impacting on BATSA\'92s obligation to make good on its side of the bargain, that is to continue making the full incentive payments that had been agreed upon.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 149.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch van Vuuren\'92s interpretation of the terms of his agreement with BATSA may reflect little more than the dynamics between a powerful buyer at South Africa\'92s largest grocery chain and a supplier.  More likely, and for the sake of argument we should assume this
 to be case, it indicates that, regardless of whether or not its planograms had been formally endorsed by Pick n Pay, the actual extent of conformity between what BATSA desired and what was acceptable to Pick n Pay and therefore implemented was sufficientl
y close for BATSA to continue making the incentive payments.  The much debated case of the northern Gauteng region of Pick n Pay appears to demonstrate that when the CDUs ceased to reflect in any way BATSA\'92s planograms either with respect to space or posit
ioning, BATSA stopped making payments in respect of that region to the retail chain. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 150.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch The 2007 agreement with Pick n Pay supermarkets makes reference to a 90:10 space allocation as between BATSA, on the one hand, and the brands of other manufacturers, on the other. van Vuuren insists that this was not applied.  It clearly reflects BATSA\'92s s
tated aspiration that space allocated in all channels reflects its national market share \'96 indeed this is somewhat higher than its 2007 national market share.  Moreover the national share is skewed by BATSA\'92s particularly large share in independent conveni
ence and the \'91main market\'92 in particular, and is certainly higher than the grocery share. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 151.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch We would conclude from this that the organisation of the cigarette POS in Pick n Pay supermarkets generally conformed to BATSA\'92s planograms and contractual terms.  However they were clearly not applied unexceptionally.  We have already referred to the Wate
rfront store where the demographics and demand patterns of the clientele appear to have accounted for a significant departure from BATSA planograms and in which store management accorded Marlboro pride of place both with respect to allocations of space and
 position.  It does not appear that incentive payments due in respect of this store were withheld because of this instance of non-compliance, nor is it clear how many other similar instances of non-compliance occurred.  The decentralised nature of the Pick
 n Pay operation would have facilitated deviations from the national norm and would account for the northern Gauteng rebellion, the most widely discussed instance of non-compliance which we deal with below.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 152.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\rtlch The most plausible conclusion to be drawn from van Vuuren\'92s evidence is that while the shelf space and positioning allocations used in the cigarette category in his region conformed broadly with BATSA\'92s planograms, this is principally because, while they d
id not entirely conform to van Vuuren\'92s view and thus were never formally agreed, they were nevertheless not thought to conflict fundamentally with Pick n Pay\'92s own interests. It is difficult to believe that the incentive payments were not factored into Pi
ck n Pay\'92s interest and that they did not exercise some influence on the organisation of Pick n Pay\'92s CDUs, but they certainly do not appear to have been the only factor. van Vuuren believed emphatically that he was entitled to the payments regardless of w
hether or not he implemented BATSA\'92s planograms and there is clear evidence of significant deviation from BATSA\'92s planograms when the demographics and demand patterns of a particular store warranted it. This is all of a piece with van Vuuren\'92s blunt assert
ion, already cited, that }}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i \'91the best form of category management depends on the strategy of the retailer\'92}{\rtlch.}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 153.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch van Vuuren\'92s approach and his refusal to be bound by BATSA\'92s planograms also lends weight to his assertion that he would be prepared to consider a planogram presented by any supplier who met his minimum condition for participation in the category managemen
t process, namely  that it purchases Pick n Pay\'92s EPOS data.  Indeed as indicated above, van Vuuren testified \'96 and we do not understand this testimony to have been challenged - that since JTI and PMI have commenced paying for the EPOS data they have been 
permitted input into the holy sanctum of planogramming.  As with Shoprite Checkers we do not believe that this would have extended to significant compromise on the \'91hot spot\'92 display \'96 this is, after all, the central aspect of the limited exclusive that BA
TSA has purchased - but the evidence suggests that it may well improve both the positioning and the space allocated to BATSA\'92s rivals without resulting in a withholding of the incentive payment.  As elaborated below we believe that the northern Gauteng inc
ident bears out this contention.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 154.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\rtlch The reasonable conclusion to draw \'96 both with respect to Shoprite Checkers and Pick n Pay supermarkets - is that JTI\'92s lack of influence at the POS was in significant part attributable to its reluctance to expend any resources on promotion, even including 
purchasing the EPOS data, a threshold condition for participating in category management.  Indeed even beyond JTI\'92s refusal to purchase the EPOS data and its effective abdication from participation in the planogramming process, both Ackerman and van Vuuren
 were clearly struck by what can only be described as JTI\'92s starkly supine attitude towards trade marketing in the grocery channel.  Witnesses from the retail trade persistently remarked upon the sparse attempts at contact made by JTI.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\sl240\slmult1\ql{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs68\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs20\lang7177\i0\b0 Witness Statement Bundle p461-2 and T2471-2; Witness Statement Bundle p1246 and T4884, 4957 and 4951; Ackerman Witness Statement par 5.4.}}}
{\*\cs68\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up9\rtlch\af11\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f0\fs24\lang1033\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\af2 }{\rtlch\af2  }}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 155.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\rtlch We hasten to add that JTI\'92s refusal to expend time and money on trade marketing in the organised grocery channel may well reflect a rational, considered commercial decision on its part. Like van Vuuren and Ackerman we are sceptical of the promotional power
 of the organised grocery POS, particularly given the channel\'92s relatively low contribution to cigarette sales and the demographics of its customers.  It makes perfect sense for a manufacturer with constrained resources to abandon promotional activity at t
he grocery channel\'92s point of sale, particularly as the }}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\ul\ulc0\rtlch limited}{\rtlch exclusive and the retailers\'92 listing requirement guaranteed it a POS presence without, we should add, having to spend a cent. Moreover, BATSA\'92s category captaincy ensured a neat, uncluttered P
OS and CDU.  However, if JTI has indeed decided, on solid commercial grounds, not to expend its trade marketing resources in organised grocery, it behoves us to adopt a sceptical approach to a strategy that seeks to invoke competition law in order to neutr
alise BATSA\'92s promotional expenditure, largely by permitting JTI to free ride on its rival\'92s efforts.}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 156.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch Our reluctance to permit JTI to use legal  stratagem to blunt its rival\'92s efforts at trade marketing is bolstered by the observation that where JTI did elect to expend resources on trade marketing, even in organised retail, it succeeded in wresting promoti
onal opportunities from BATSA. As mentioned above, when JTI eventually decided to purchase the Pick n Pay EPOS data it was given input into planogramming.  This does not mean that it would have displaced BATSA from the hot spot or even that it would have b
een allowed to ascend from the bottom left hand corner of the CDU.  In order to do this it \'96 presumably with the support of PMI - would have to have used its opportunity to make input in order to demonstrate to the retailer that the present arrangement reg
arding space and position redounds to the ultimate detriment of the retailer and its customers, precisely the case that it claims to make here.  Their arguments would have undoubtedly entailed the offer of an incentive payment, an important consideration i
n the advantage that accrues to both retailer and customer from the present arrangement.  That is to say, appeals to the \'91principles\'92 of category management are extremely unlikely to suffice in the real world. However, as noted above, we believe that a com
bination of factors would enable BATSA\'92s rivals to make some headway with respect to space and positioning without the retailer risking the withholding of BATSA\'92s entire incentive payment.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 157.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch This is, we believe, demonstrated by the northern Gauteng incident. To cut short a story debated at inordinate length, it appears that the Pick n Pay buyer for the northern Gauteng region insisted on placing Camel in the top shelves alongside the other pre
mium brands. BATSA objected. The positioning of its rival was nevertheless improved along the lines desired by the northern Gauteng buyer and the amount of space allocated to BATSA was reduced significantly. It appears that BATSA initially continued making
 its incentive payments with the exception of the payments in respect of the planogramming driver.  However, far from dissuading the buyer from continuing along this path, BATSA\'92s position, both in term of space and position continued to deteriorate with a
 concomitant improvement in Camel\'92s allocations of space and position, including in relation to its privileged place in the hallowed \'91hot spot\'92.  Ultimately BATSA concluded, in the words of its representative, that it was \'91paying for nothing\'92 and withheld 
its entire incentive payment.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 158.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }}{{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0 As far as we are able to glean \'96 and the evidence is not clear \'96 the northern Gauteng buyer\'92s demands did not arise as a result of any sudden outraged sense of fairness or even commercial epiphany on his part regarding the appropriate location of Camel in
 the CDU, but rather in consequence of unusually robust trade marketing, including the offer of a competing incentive, on the part of JTI. Indeed JTI effectively bid to become category manager, a bid in which the persuasiveness of its representatives was b
acked up by the payment of a considerable incentive.  }}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 159.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch This incident has received the degree of attention that it has because, allege the applicants, it reveals the \'91all or nothing\'92 character of BATSA\'92s incentive package, the refusal of BATSA to sever one element of its incentive package from another.  We are 
not confident that it conclusively clarifies BATSA\'92s position on severability, although we are constrained to observe that it certainly does establish that it is, at least, possible to compete for promotional opportunities in Pick n Pay on a regional basis
.  That is to say, it establishes that a rival to BATSA did not have to secure promotional privileges or category captaincy across the national Pick n Pay supermarket chain, but rather that it was possible to contend for a particular region. This alone cal
ls into question the \'91all or nothing\'92 contention advanced by the applicants, at least as it applied to Pick n Pay.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 160.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\rtlch On the question of the severability of one driver from another, we believe that the northern Gauteng incident reveals that, to a degree, there is indeed severability.  That is to say, BATSA will accept quite significant deviations from its planogram \'96 espe
cially where the quantum of space allocated to it is concerned \'96 and, at most although not inevitably, withhold its incentive payment in respect of the planogram driver only, while continuing to make good on the other incentive payments. Nor is this surpri
