\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 163.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\rtlch The applicants make much of the provision by BATSA of free merchandising equipment, most notably the costly macrobat CDUs.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\sl240\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs68\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs20\lang7177\i0\b0{ A macrobat is an open back wall unit containing cigarettes in open shelves. A pacrobat is a gravity dispenser or overheard unit which is usually on top of the till and contains cigarettes which will largely be out of sight of the customer. The cashier, an
d not the customer, has sole access to the macrobat and the pacrobat. (T2092-3)}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs20\lang7177\i0\b0{\cf3  }}}}
{\*\cs68\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up9\rtlch\af11\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f0\fs24\lang1033\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\af2 }{\rtlch\af2   In particularly, they seek to establish an interface between the provision of the merchandising furniture and the plannogramming ri
ghts.  They point to clauses in the equipment loan agreements (ELAs) \'96 the agreements that govern the provision of the merchandising equipment - that make reference to plannogramming rights. They argue that the duration of the ELAs \'96 typically five years \'96
 effectively extends the duration of, ensures the roll over of, the much shorter trade merchandising agreements because the presence of BATSA furniture, and the prospect that BATSA may, in the event of failing to renew its trade merchandising agreements, t
erminate the ELA.  BATSA, for its part, points out that the ELAs are concluded on a store-by-store basis and are not part of the remit of the trade merchandising teams.}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 164.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\rtlch While all of this may be true we are not persuaded by what is effectively the applicants\'92 core contention in this regard, namely that BATSA would withdraw its CDUs in order to enforce and extend its trade merchandising rights.  The provision of free CDUs r
epresents an extremely costly investment on BATSA\'92s part, particularly in organised retail, where the retailers value achieving a similar look and feel across its branches.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\sl240\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs68\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs20\lang7177\i0\b0 See JTI HOA para 7.64.1 in which the evidence estimating the cost of CDU provision is estimated.   Mr. Ackerman estimated that by 2000 BATSA had invested R21 million in furniture in Shoprite Checkers alone, an amount more than five times larger than the t
otal annual incentives paid to Shoprite Checkers in terms of the BATSA agreements.{\cf3  }}}}
{\*\cs68\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up9\rtlch\af11\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f0\fs24\lang1033\loch\f0\fs24\lang1033\rtlch\af2 }{\rtlch\af2   BATSA will undoubtedly attempt to recoup as much of this investment as possible a
nd so may well suggest a linkage between, on the one hand, continued access to this equipment and, on the other, the enforcement of its limited exclusive, and particularly the planogramming driver.  On the other hand it is a very valuable benefit to the re
cipients and so any prospect of losing the CDUs may be a powerful incentive for compliance.  However, on any sensible construction, BATSA\'92s actual ability to withdraw its CDUs, particularly in organised retail, is extremely limited.  By withdrawing CDUs fr
om a small number of non-compliant stores in a chain, the retailers\'92 efforts to achieve a similar look and feel is immediately undermined. It is unthinkable that BATSA would, in the event of a disagreement with, say, Shoprite Checkers start withdrawing its
 CDUs. The loss of goodwill that this would entail would severely damage the relationship between BATSA and a significant customer.  In this little corner of the world, removal of the CDUs is equivalent to exercising the nuclear option and the likelihood o
f that is close to zero.}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 165.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch We have no doubt that the provision of free merchandising equipment purchases significant goodwill for BATSA and that BATSA will seek to milk this to the maximum extent possible, in particular by attempting to assert a linkage between the free CDUs and com
pliance on space and positioning. However, we are of the view that, for the most part, it represents an investment in the category, an investment which only BATSA would make on a significant scale.  Certainly, the counterfactual, less adequate CDUs or the 
retailers paying for the equipment itself, will result in either a less well managed and presented category or significantly less pass-through to end consumers.  It is telling that for all that the applicants seek to make of the threat posed by removal of 
the CDUs, we cannot recall a single example \'96 even from independent retail where BATSA\'92s ability to contain any possible fall out resulting from a withdrawal of a freely provided CDU is much greater \'96 of BATSA having acted, or even having threatened to act
, on this.   As noted Pick n Pay has installed its own CDUs \'96 though with support from BATSA \'96 in preference to using free BATSA-owned CDUs.  This preference is rooted in Pick n Pay\'92s desire to remain independent of its suppliers.  While this indicates tha
t Pick n Pay believes that free CDUs could be used as leverage by BATSA, we do not believe that, once installed, the threat of withdrawal is credible.  Indeed Pick n Pay also helps to establish that compliance with BATSA\'92s desired POS arrangements did not 
depend upon the provision of free merchandising equipment. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 166.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch It appears that the in-store merchandising architecture driver is more concerned with the requirement to remove non-tobacco products from the CDU and the placement of secondary promotional materials at the POS than with the plannogramming of the CDU.  The 
former requirement \'96 to keep the CDU free of non-tobacco products \'96 brings no particular advantage to BATSA. Category promotion is clearly the consideration here.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
