f BATSA\'92s competitors, grant BATSA more than a limited exclusive, that is regardless of the incentive offered by BATSA, they will ensure that non-BATSA brands are allocated space and that they are displayed, albeit in inferior positions.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi0\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 202.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s4\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li284\ri0\lin284\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch Indeed, as BATSA has pointed out \'96 and this does not seem to have been contested \'96 the organised grocery and convenience channel certainly, and very probably, the organised forecourt channel, appear to go beyond the application of strict category managemen
t considerations in their approach to the listing of small brands and SKU\'92s.  It has never been suggested to us that the retailers in any of the channels \'96 with the obvious exception of the highly space-constrained vending machine operators \'96 have refused 
to list and place a new brand or even SKU on the CDU.  The applicants have sought to make something of the provision contained in many of the BATSA agreements that require the retailers in question to stock all BATSA brands and SKUs.  In truth, though, thi
s clause seems superfluous because, from most accounts, it appears that the retailers, of their own volition, insist on listing and displaying all available brands and SKUs, regardless of the manufacturer from whom they emanate. The inevitable upshot of th
