\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li295\ri0\lin295\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 235.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li295\ri0\lin295\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0\rtlch The applicants have attempted to persuade us of the significance of POS promotional activities through, firstly, the assertion of general marketing theories that are, we believe, of limited applicability to the peculiar circumstances of cigarette retailing
 and, for the most part, serve to negate rather than promote competition.  Secondly, the applicants have sought to persuade us to infer that BATSA\'92s willingness to devote considerable resources to POS promotion in the retail channels establishes that BATSA
 itself believes this to be an important promotional site.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\chcbpat8\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-709\rtlch\af2\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li295\ri0\lin295\rin0\fi-360\f2\fs22\lang7177\f0\fs22\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl276\slmult1\qj 236.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl276\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li295\ri0\lin295\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af0\langfe255\hich\f2\fs22\lang7177\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\rtlch We have stated our view on category management principles at length and will not repeat these here. We should though note that it has been suggested that marketing advantage accrues to BATSA from the bill board or \'91big brand\'92 effect that is created as a re
sult of blanketing the CDU \'91hot spot\'92 with a single brand.  This is lent credence by evidence suggesting that BATSA has made some effort to split the displays of other brands.  There may be some validity in the big brand effect argument.  It is impossible 
to evaluate \'96 even qualitatively \'96 its impact or to remedy it without imposing a highly invasive set of regulations on the retail POS.}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs22\lang7177\i0\b0{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s13\sl240\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs68\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs20\lang7177\i0\b0{ Mr. Botha asserted that \'91}}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f2\fs20\lang7177\i0\b0{\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i one of the key issues of displaying products is trying to make your product look bigger than it is.  So you\'92re always looking for opportunities to get mass displays and bigger displays to make the product look big\'85\'92 }{cited CC HOA p
ara 7.3.4.  If the CDUs are to be relied upon to \'91make the product look big\'92 then, in a dark market, on the application of the strictest category management principles (where brand shares rather than manufacturers shares are used to allocate space), Peter 
Stuyvesant\'92s \'91bigness\'92 would dwarf all other brands.   To the extent that this \'91big brand\'92 effect is indeed an important means of brand promotion, the application of category management principles would then exacerbate the effect that we believe is, in any
 event, caused by dark market conditions, namely that of freezing market shares and acting as an absolute barrier to new entry.  Certainly by appealing to category management principles Mr. Botha could not have expected a CDU display to make his brand \'91loo
k big\'92 for the simple reason that its market share was miniscule.  BATSA was able to make a small brand like Lucky Strike \'91look big\'92 by purchasing a limited exclusive and, on the basis of manufacturer\'92s share, by sacrificing space that would have, followin
g category management principles, been allocated to one of its big brands, inevitably Stuyvesant.  We should add \'96 as already noted \'96 that Lucky Strike seemed incapable of growing its market share despite the marketing and trade investment attention that h
as been lavished on it. }}}}
